---
import Container from "../components/Container.astro";
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Label from "../components/Label.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="Privacy"
  description="How this site handles your data: privacy-first, cookieless analytics with Fathom, no tracking, and no personal data."
>
  <Container section id="privacy" className="md:max-w-2xl">
    <Label>Privacy</Label>
    <h1 class="mt-3 text-4xl">Privacy</h1>

    <p class="mt-5">
      The short version: this site doesn't track you, sets no cookies, and —
      unless you choose to subscribe to the newsletter — collects nothing that
      could identify you. There's no consent banner because there's nothing to
      consent to.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl">Analytics</h2>
    <p class="mt-4">
      I use <a href="https://usefathom.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
        >Fathom Analytics</a
      >, a privacy-first, cookieless analytics service, to see which pages get
      read and where visitors arrive from — in aggregate only. It's designed so
      I can spot useful trends without ever knowing who you are.
    </p>

    <p class="mt-4">What Fathom records, all aggregated and anonymous:</p>
    <ul class="text-body mt-3 list-disc space-y-1 pl-5">
      <li>Page views and the paths visitors take through the site</li>
      <li>The referrer — the site or search you arrived from</li>
      <li>Country, derived from your IP (which is never stored)</li>
      <li>Browser and device type</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="mt-4">
      I also record a few anonymous interaction events — such as a newsletter
      signup, a download, an audio play, or a search — so I can see which
      features actually get used. These are aggregate counts only, with nothing
      that identifies you and no content (your search terms and email are never
      part of an event).
    </p>

    <p class="mt-4">
      IP addresses are processed only briefly — for security and to generate an
      anonymous, hashed visitor signature — and are never stored with the
      analytics data or included in any export. Visitors in the EU have their
      data processed on EU-based servers. Fathom is GDPR, CCPA, ePrivacy/PECR,
      and Schrems II compliant; you can read their full data policy at <a
        href="https://usefathom.com/data"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener">usefathom.com/data</a
      >.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl">Newsletter</h2>
    <p class="mt-4">
      The newsletter is entirely optional and opt-in. If you subscribe, your
      email address is stored and processed by <a
        href="https://kit.com/privacy"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener">Kit</a
      > (formerly ConvertKit), the service that manages the list and sends the emails,
      for the sole purpose of sending you new essays and the occasional tool. It's
      double opt-in — you confirm before anything is sent — and every email has a
      one-click unsubscribe. I never sell or share your address, and you can leave
      anytime.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl">Cookies</h2>
    <p class="mt-4">
      None. This site sets no tracking or advertising cookies, which is exactly
      why you won't see a cookie banner.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-4">
      The only thing stored in your browser is a small preference — your choice
      of light or dark theme — kept in <code>localStorage</code>. It never
      leaves your device, isn't a cookie, and is sent to no one. Clearing your
      browser storage removes it.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl">In-browser tools</h2>
    <p class="mt-4">
      The voice generator runs entirely on your device. The text you type and
      the audio it produces never leave your browser — there's no server doing
      the work. The one-time model download comes from a public CDN, which sees
      only the request (as any file download would), not your text or audio.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl">Hosting &amp; files</h2>
    <p class="mt-4">
      The site is static and served by Cloudflare Pages, and downloads and media
      are served from Cloudflare too. Like any web host, Cloudflare may
      transiently process request data (such as IP addresses) to deliver files
      and guard against abuse, under its own policies.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-12 text-2xl">Questions</h2>
    <p class="mt-4">
      Any questions about privacy here? Reach me through any of the links in the
      footer.
    </p>

    <p class="mt-10 text-xs">Last updated: July 2026</p>
  </Container>
</Layout>
